## Error Handling

- Never let Supabase errors fail silently — always check `error` and handle it
- In Server Actions: `throw new Error(message)` — Next.js will catch it
- In Client Components: use `try/catch` and set local error state
- Never expose raw Supabase error messages to the UI — map them to user-friendly strings
- Use TypeScript's `unknown` for caught errors, not `any`

```ts
// ✅ Server Action error handling
export async function updateBlock(id: string, data: Partial<Block>) {
  const supabase = createClient()
  const { error } = await supabase.from('blocks').update(data).eq('id', id)
  if (error) throw new Error('Failed to update block. Please try again.')
  revalidatePath('/plan/[id]')
}

// ✅ Client Component error handling
try {
  await updateBlock(id, data)
} catch (err: unknown) {
  const message = err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'Something went wrong'
  setError(message)
}
```

---

## General Rules

- No `console.log` left in committed code — use comments or remove
- No hardcoded strings for routes — use constants or `href` helpers
- No barrel files (`index.ts` re-exports) unless the folder has 4+ exports
- Keep components under 200 lines — split into sub-components if longer
- Co-locate sub-components with their parent if used nowhere else
- All environment variables accessed via `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_*` must be declared in `.env.local` and `.env.example`